Central America
---
Costa Rica. 4 May 2016. (conf.) 14 cases locally acquired, 5 cases imported, 2 ex Colombia and Nicaragua, 1 ex Honduras. Localities affected: Nicoya 8 cases, Carrillo 1 case, Alajuelita 5 cases.
http://www.teletica.com/Noticias/123923-Salud-confirma-que-14-personas-han-sido-contagiadas-con-el-virus-del-zika.note.aspx [in Spanish]

Honduras. 7 May 2016. (reported) more than 19 000 cases; Gjillain-Barré syndrome 78 cases [but no indication if previously Zika virus infected]. Departments most affected: Cortés, Francisco Morazán, Yoro, Choluteca.
http://www.prensa-latina.cu/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=4859021&Itemid=1 [in Spanish]

[A 9 May 2016 report indicates that Honduras health authorities strongly suspect that they have their 1st case of microcephaly in the fetus of a 5-month pregnant woman, although it is not stated that she has had a confirmed Zika virus infection. Honduras has 238 pregnant women with Zika virus infections. (http://wiky.com/news/articles/2016/may/09/honduras-suspects-first-case-of-microcephaly-in-pregnant-zika-patient/).

El Salvador. 4 May 2016. (susp.) 6361 cases, (conf.) 43 cases.
http://www.elsalvador.com/articulo/nacional/salud-reporta-mil-casos-sospechosos-entre-dengue-chikunguna-zika-111607 [in Spanish]

Nicaragua. 6 May 2016. (conf.) 182 cases. Locality most affected: Managua.
http://www.elnuevodiario.com.ni/nacionales/391957-nicaragua-acumula-182-casos-zika/ [in Spanish]

Panama. 5 May 2016. (reported) 264 cases of whom 14 are pregnant; 6 babies infected with Zika virus and born with malformations, of whom 4 are microcephalic.
http://www.boursorama.com/actualites/quatre-cas-de-microcephalie-lies-au-virus-zika-au-panama-b73ed3450f42b7d80ab2bc7d5fc1f100
(in French, trans. Corr.SB )

